    <item>
      <title>Blockquotes</title>
      <link>https://flittle8.github.io/cupper/patterns/structure-and-semantics/blockquotes/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://flittle8.github.io/cupper/patterns/structure-and-semantics/blockquotes/</guid>
      <description>A blockquote represents a section that is quoted from another source. It&amp;rsquo;s represented by the &amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt; element.
Often times, you will see books that use the &amp;lt;p&amp;gt; or paragraph element, instead of the semantically correct &amp;lt;blockquote&amp;gt;. This &amp;lt;p&amp;gt; element is often followed by a class=&amp;quot;quote&amp;quot; attribute, or a similiar class value (we&amp;rsquo;ll talk more about getting rid of classes later).
Using the &amp;lt;p&amp;gt; element when a more specific element is appropriate is a violation of the HTML specification.</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Bold and italics</title>
      <link>https://flittle8.github.io/cupper/patterns/structure-and-semantics/bold-italics/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://flittle8.github.io/cupper/patterns/structure-and-semantics/bold-italics/</guid>
      <description>Strong vs. Bold. Emphasis vs. Italics. What&amp;rsquo;s the difference? And what should we do about it?
In HTML5, there are two types of &amp;ldquo;bold&amp;rdquo; - represented by the &amp;lt;strong&amp;gt; and the &amp;lt;b&amp;gt; elements. There also two types of &amp;ldquo;italics&amp;rdquo; - represented by the &amp;lt;em&amp;gt; and the &amp;lt;i&amp;gt; elements. Each of these elements convey different information to the reading system. If you&amp;rsquo;re curious about their uses, you can explore the links in the References.</description>
    </item>
    
